==Living former Secretaries of Housing and Urban Development==
{{see also|List of living former members of the United States Cabinet}}
[[Image:RomneySwornInSecHUD.jpg|thumb|right|[[George W. Romney]] was sworn in as Secretary of Housing and Urban Development on January 22, 1969, with President [[Richard Nixon]] in attendance.]]
As of {{Monthyear}}, there are nine living former Secretaries of Housing and Urban Development (with all Secretaries that have served since 1993 still living), the oldest being [[Moon Landrieu|Maurice E. Landrieu]] (served 1979–1981, born 1930). The most recent Secretary of Housing and Urban Development to die was [[James Thomas Lynn|James T. Lynn]] (served 1973–1975, born 1927), who died on December 6, 2010. The most recently-serving Secretary to die was [[Jack Kemp]] (served 1989–1993, born 1935) on May 2, 2009.

